[[File:Leeds1984.png|right|thumb|500px|Map of the results for the 1984 Leeds council election.]]

The '''[[Leeds City Council]] elections''' were held on Thursday, 3 May 1984, with one third of the council to be elected. In the interim there had been a by-election in [[Armley (ward)|Armley]] to replace the incumbent councillor [[Michael Meadowcroft]] after he was elected the [[Leeds West (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds West]] MP, resulting in an [[SDP-Liberal Alliance|Alliance]] hold.

The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative's]] downward trend continued after [[Leeds City Council election, 1983|last year's]] respite to a new party low, resulting in a 3% swing to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]. In contrast, the Alliance support stabilised after the prior year's fall to retain a healthy proportion of their initial [[Leeds City Council election, 1982|1982 surge]]. Despite the swing towards them, Labour finished the night with a net loss, as the Alliance won the only remaining [[Burmantofts]] seat they did not hold from them. The Alliance also gained in [[Moortown, Leeds|Moortown]], winning their first seat in the ward from the Conservatives - who lost another in [[Pudsey]] South to their former incumbent turn [[Independent (politician)|Independent]], achieving the feat of first elected Independent onto the council.<ref name="results">{{cite news |title=District results: Leeds |work=[[The Yorkshire Post]] |page= |date=4 May 1984}}</ref>

